1
00:00:14,222 --> 00:00:15,807
Quiet on the set.

2
00:00:17,475 --> 00:00:19,519
Scene one, take ten.
Marker.

3
00:00:26,818 --> 00:00:29,362
And action!

4
00:00:31,614 --> 00:00:33,575
Joel Levison's office.

5
00:00:33,658 --> 00:00:37,203
I'm sorry, he's not in yet.
May I take a message?

6
00:00:37,287 --> 00:00:40,081
- Mr. Levy, I'll tell him you called.
- Never say that.

7
00:00:40,165 --> 00:00:43,501
He's either in conference, in a meeting.
He's always in.

8
00:00:43,585 --> 00:00:45,754
- Who was that?
- Larry Levy.

9
00:00:47,130 --> 00:00:49,632
Was there anything in the trades
this morning?

10
00:00:49,716 --> 00:00:53,261
- I don't know. The mail's late.
- Go get them. Now!

11
00:00:53,344 --> 00:00:56,556
I want them back here
before he arrives.

12
00:01:11,488 --> 00:01:15,533
Griffin, hi. Adam Simon.

13
00:01:15,617 --> 00:01:17,952
We weren't supposed to meet
until next week, but-

14
00:01:18,036 --> 00:01:22,081
- I didn't know we were.
- I wanted to plant a seed in your head.

15
00:01:22,165 --> 00:01:24,667
- I'm booked up.
- Picture this.

16
00:01:24,751 --> 00:01:27,420
It's a planet in the far future
with two suns.

17
00:01:27,462 --> 00:01:29,714
- Who plays the sons?
- No, suns. Large solar disks.

18
00:01:29,797 --> 00:01:31,716
Run this idea by Bonnie Sherow.

19
00:01:31,799 --> 00:01:35,178
The pictures they make these days
are all MTV. Cut, cut, cut.

20
00:01:35,261 --> 00:01:38,723
The opening shot of Touch of Evil
was six and a half minutes long.

21
00:01:38,806 --> 00:01:41,267
- Six and a half minutes?
- Three or four, anyway.

22
00:01:41,351 --> 00:01:44,562
He set up the whole picture
with that one tracking shot.

23
00:01:44,646 --> 00:01:47,023
My father was key grip on that shoot.

24
00:01:47,106 --> 00:01:51,319
What about Absolute Beginners?
That was an extraordinary shot.

25
00:01:51,361 --> 00:01:54,656
- Never heard of it.
- It's an English film.

26
00:01:59,035 --> 00:02:02,121
- A Peligrino, please.
- I've got Calistoga.

27
00:02:02,205 --> 00:02:04,249
- Buck, how are you?
- Good. How you doin'?

28
00:02:04,332 --> 00:02:08,670
- Good. What have you got for me?
- Okay, here it is.

29
00:02:08,753 --> 00:02:11,589
- The Graduate, Part II.
- Oh, good.

30
00:02:11,673 --> 00:02:14,676
Listen, the three principals
are still with us.

31
00:02:14,759 --> 00:02:20,223
Dustin Hoffman, Anne Bancroft,
Katharine Ross, 25 years later.

32
00:02:20,306 --> 00:02:25,270
And so are the characters,
Ben, Elaine and Mrs. Robinson.

33
00:02:25,353 --> 00:02:27,272
Ben and Elaine are married, still.

34
00:02:27,355 --> 00:02:32,026
They live in a big, spooky house
up in northern California somewhere.

35
00:02:32,110 --> 00:02:35,196
And Mrs. Robinson
lives with them...

36
00:02:35,280 --> 00:02:39,993
her aging mother
who's had a stroke...

37
00:02:40,034 --> 00:02:41,995
so she can't talk.

38
00:02:42,036 --> 00:02:45,623
- Will it be funny?
- It'll be funny. Dark, weird and funny.

39
00:02:45,707 --> 00:02:49,043
And with a stroke.
Maybe it's not a stroke.

40
00:02:49,127 --> 00:02:51,796
I don't know what it is.
It's a malady of some sort.

41
00:02:51,879 --> 00:02:55,466
She's up in the bedroom listening
to everything that happens.

42
00:02:55,550 --> 00:02:58,469
They've got a daughter
who's just graduated from college.

43
00:02:58,553 --> 00:03:02,890
Twenty-two, twenty-three-year-old,
like a Julia Roberts.

44
00:03:02,932 --> 00:03:04,976
Excuse me.
What should I do with these scripts?

45
00:03:05,059 --> 00:03:10,398
They go to Bonnie. And find out from
security how Adam Simon got on the lot.

46
00:03:10,440 --> 00:03:14,402
- I want to know.
- Adam Simon? Okay.

47
00:03:14,485 --> 00:03:17,572
Julia Roberts comes home,
their daughter, the graduate.

48
00:03:17,655 --> 00:03:19,490
The new graduate.

49
00:03:19,574 --> 00:03:22,201
Griffin loved it.
He wanted me to run it by you.

50
00:03:22,285 --> 00:03:27,623
- It's a band of human survivors.
- Write this down for me.

51
00:03:27,707 --> 00:03:30,793
I can't process this.
Write it down for me.

52
00:03:30,877 --> 00:03:34,005
It's not about words.
You have to visualize.

53
00:03:37,383 --> 00:03:41,471
Jimmy, are you okay?
What happened?

54
00:03:42,805 --> 00:03:46,350
- Are you all right?
- My name's Jimmy Chase.

55
00:03:48,394 --> 00:03:52,064
He came out of nowhere, ran right
in front of the cart. I never saw him.

56
00:03:57,028 --> 00:03:59,322
- That's Adam Simon.
- How you doin', kid?

57
00:04:08,748 --> 00:04:12,126
Rebecca DeMornay.
Actually, you're better looking.

58
00:04:12,168 --> 00:04:15,254
- No, I'm not Rebecca DeMornay.
- You're a dead ringer.

59
00:04:15,296 --> 00:04:17,006
Thank you very much.

60
00:04:17,089 --> 00:04:19,842
Do you know where
Joel Levison's office is?

61
00:04:19,926 --> 00:04:22,762
The head of the studio?

62
00:04:22,803 --> 00:04:24,764
It's moving.
It'll rip your heart out.

63
00:04:24,805 --> 00:04:29,685
This is the area where we make decisions
to give a green light to a picture.

64
00:04:29,769 --> 00:04:34,273
We're going to go 17 stories high.
We'll continue to use all Sony products.

65
00:04:34,315 --> 00:04:37,360
Domo arigato to the Sony products.

66
00:04:37,443 --> 00:04:41,948
If you need someone to eat sashimi
with you, give me a ring.

67
00:04:48,204 --> 00:04:50,498
The traffic from Malibu
was impossible.

68
00:04:50,581 --> 00:04:54,168
- Good morning, Joel.
- Sandy, park the car, please.

69
00:04:54,252 --> 00:04:56,254
Good morning Marty, Annie.

70
00:04:58,381 --> 00:05:03,052
- What are the Japs doing here?
- What's this talk about heads rolling?

71
00:05:03,135 --> 00:05:06,264
The bank's putting screws to us.
Goldman's son is coming out from Boston.

72
00:05:06,347 --> 00:05:07,765
I don't like it.

73
00:05:07,848 --> 00:05:11,310
Reggie Goldman's a pipsqueak.
You can't be serious.

74
00:05:11,352 --> 00:05:15,606
Some changes are going on here.
That's always the way.

75
00:05:15,690 --> 00:05:18,526
It happened at Paramount
three years ago.

76
00:05:18,567 --> 00:05:20,653
Columbia's going through it now.

77
00:05:20,736 --> 00:05:23,030
I hear we're looking
to replace Griffin.

78
00:05:23,072 --> 00:05:25,408
Griffin? I don't believe it.
With whom?

79
00:05:25,491 --> 00:05:28,869
Burke or Patrick.
Maybe Larry Levy.

80
00:05:28,953 --> 00:05:32,665
I want to know why
the security is lax.

81
00:05:32,707 --> 00:05:35,710
I'll talk to you later.
I'm in the middle of a pitch.

82
00:05:35,793 --> 00:05:37,962
Listen, go ahead.

83
00:05:38,045 --> 00:05:43,342
- It's a TV star who goes on a safari.
- A TV star in a motion picture?

84
00:05:43,384 --> 00:05:48,347
- A TV star played by a movie star.
- A movie star playing a TV star.

85
00:05:48,389 --> 00:05:52,727
- Michelle, Bette, Lily.
- Dolly Parton would be good.

86
00:05:52,810 --> 00:05:58,065
- I like Goldie.
- Great, because we have a relationship.

87
00:05:58,149 --> 00:06:00,609
Goldie goes to Africa.

88
00:06:00,693 --> 00:06:06,365
- She's found by this tribe.
- Of small people.

89
00:06:06,449 --> 00:06:09,326
She's found and they worship her.

90
00:06:09,410 --> 00:06:14,206
It's like The Gods Must Be Crazy
except the coke bottle is an actress.

91
00:06:14,248 --> 00:06:16,876
Right. It's Out of Africa
meets Pretty Woman.

92
00:06:16,959 --> 00:06:20,546
She has to decide whether to stay
with the TV show...

93
00:06:20,588 --> 00:06:23,090
or save the tribe.

94
00:06:23,174 --> 00:06:26,135
- Where's Griffin Mill's office?
- Right here.

95
00:06:26,218 --> 00:06:29,138
- You're Martin Scorsese!
- No, but I know Harvey Keitel.

96
00:06:29,221 --> 00:06:32,725
I know you do.
I loved Cape Fear.

97
00:06:32,767 --> 00:06:35,478
My old man worked for Hitchcock.

98
00:06:35,561 --> 00:06:37,813
Rope. It was a masterpiece.

99
00:06:37,897 --> 00:06:40,691
The story wasn't any good.
He shot the whole thing without cuts.

100
00:06:40,775 --> 00:06:42,651
I hate all this 'Cut, cut, cut!'

101
00:06:42,735 --> 00:06:48,240
What about Bertolucci, the great shot
with Winger in Sheltering Sky?

102
00:06:48,282 --> 00:06:50,367
I didn't see it.

103
00:06:53,746 --> 00:06:57,750
- I've been here since 8:00.
- I took a chance getting you this job.

104
00:06:57,833 --> 00:07:01,796
- Who were you with?
- I was with Alan Rudolph.

105
00:07:01,879 --> 00:07:06,801
- What were you doing with him?
- He asked me to have coffee.

106
00:07:06,842 --> 00:07:09,428
You're my assistant.
You don't get involved with writers.

107
00:07:09,470 --> 00:07:12,389
I wasn't getting involved. I was
listening to this amazing idea he had.

108
00:07:12,473 --> 00:07:14,975
That's interesting.
What's your pitch?

109
00:07:15,059 --> 00:07:18,479
- Does political scare you?
- Political doesn't scare me.

110
00:07:18,562 --> 00:07:21,273
Radical political scares me.
Political political scares me.

111
00:07:21,315 --> 00:07:24,860
This is politely politically radical,
but it's funny.

112
00:07:24,944 --> 00:07:29,240
- It's a funny political thing.
- And it's a thriller, too, all at once.

113
00:07:29,323 --> 00:07:33,452
-What's the story?
-I want Bruce Willis. I can talk to him.

114
00:07:33,536 --> 00:07:36,997
It's a story about a bad-guy senator.

115
00:07:37,081 --> 00:07:41,544
He's traveling around the country
on the country's dime, like Sununu did.

116
00:07:41,627 --> 00:07:44,088
It's a cynical, political
thriller comedy.

117
00:07:44,171 --> 00:07:49,426
But it's got heart in the right spot.
Anyway, he has an accident.

118
00:07:49,510 --> 00:07:54,306
And he becomes clairvoyant,
like a psychic.

119
00:07:54,348 --> 00:07:57,476
So it's a psychic, political,
thriller comedy with a heart.

120
00:07:57,560 --> 00:08:01,897
With a heart, not unlike Ghost
meets Manchurian Candidate.

121
00:08:01,981 --> 00:08:05,484
- Go on, I'm listening.
- He starts reading people's minds.

122
00:08:05,568 --> 00:08:10,155
And when he gets to the President's mind
it's completely blank.

123
00:08:10,239 --> 00:08:12,491
- Can I get you anything?
- I'd like a beer, please.

124
00:08:12,533 --> 00:08:15,661
- We don't have beer.
- Red wine, please.

125
00:08:17,371 --> 00:08:22,418
Someone gets killed at the end.
They always do in political thrillers.

126
00:08:22,543 --> 00:08:26,797
- Griffin Mill's office.
- Can you put him on?

127
00:08:26,839 --> 00:08:30,593
- May I ask who's calling?
- I'd like to speak to Griffin Mill.

128
00:08:30,676 --> 00:08:34,847
He's in a meeting right now. I can take
your name and have him get back to you.

129
00:08:34,930 --> 00:08:38,309
- Excuse me?
- He'll get back to me?

130
00:08:38,350 --> 00:08:41,812
- Do you know how often I've heard this?
- Who is this?

131
00:08:41,854 --> 00:08:44,982
- If he doesn't get back to me-
- Who was that?

132
00:08:45,065 --> 00:08:48,068
- I don't know. He didn't say.
- What do you mean?

133
00:08:48,152 --> 00:08:53,449
I don't know how you'll cast it. The
lead is a 50-year-old circus performer.

134
00:08:53,532 --> 00:08:55,868
Let me read the coverage.

135
00:08:55,951 --> 00:08:58,037
Are we still having lunch
with Aaron Camp?

136
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:01,206
- What time?
- I made it for 1:00.

137
00:09:01,290 --> 00:09:03,709
- Bad day?
- He's having writer's block.

138
00:09:05,794 --> 00:09:10,257
You have a meeting with Hutter and
Frank South this afternoon at 3:00.

139
00:09:10,341 --> 00:09:14,011
I'll be here. Put this morning's
meetings on the computer. Thanks.

140
00:09:15,179 --> 00:09:18,223
- Are you going now?
- I'm going to see Levison.

141
00:09:18,307 --> 00:09:21,226
Order me a Caesar salad
and a Crystal Geyser.

142
00:09:29,276 --> 00:09:32,654
About 5:00? Thanks, Sandy.

143
00:09:32,738 --> 00:09:35,032
Hi, Sandy.

144
00:09:35,074 --> 00:09:38,202
You can't go in there!
He's in a meeting.

145
00:09:39,369 --> 00:09:42,206
It's all right, Celia.

146
00:09:42,289 --> 00:09:45,918
I don't think you've met Reg Goldman.
You know his father Harvey.

147
00:09:46,001 --> 00:09:49,713
Yes, of course. Hi, Reg.
From the bank in Boston.

148
00:09:49,797 --> 00:09:54,885
- Reg is out here for a few weeks.
- Great. Business or pleasure?

149
00:09:54,927 --> 00:09:57,554
A little of both, I hope.

150
00:09:57,596 --> 00:09:59,389
Reg is thinking of producing.

151
00:09:59,473 --> 00:10:01,475
Really?

152
00:10:01,558 --> 00:10:03,852
Yeah. Beats work,
doesn't it, Griffin?

153
00:10:03,936 --> 00:10:06,271
I'd like to play some tennis.
Do you play tennis?

154
00:10:06,355 --> 00:10:08,732
Tennis? No.

155
00:10:08,774 --> 00:10:11,443
- I'm too busy.
- I was asking Walter.

156
00:10:11,527 --> 00:10:13,862
Do you know Meg Ryan?

157
00:10:13,946 --> 00:10:15,906
Is she seeing somebody?

158
00:10:17,199 --> 00:10:19,576
Yeah, Reg. She's married.

159
00:10:20,786 --> 00:10:22,204
Shit.

160
00:10:22,287 --> 00:10:24,915
What about Winona Ryder?

161
00:10:24,998 --> 00:10:29,878
You know, actually,
Walter is the guy to talk to.

162
00:10:29,962 --> 00:10:32,297
Walter's got everybody's number.

163
00:10:32,381 --> 00:10:36,468
- Was there anything?
- No. You're real busy.

164
00:10:36,552 --> 00:10:39,930
I want that number, goddamn it.
I want that number.

165
00:10:39,972 --> 00:10:43,600
Oh, boy. What about this one?
Has she done anything?

166
00:10:44,726 --> 00:10:46,144
Celia.

167
00:10:47,563 --> 00:10:50,566
Griffin, don't ask.

168
00:10:50,649 --> 00:10:55,070
Don't ask, you don't know?
Or don't ask, I don't want to know?

169
00:10:55,153 --> 00:10:57,447
Just don't ask.

170
00:10:58,574 --> 00:11:03,328
If it's Reggie Goldman
you're concerned about, forget it.

171
00:11:03,412 --> 00:11:05,914
But be nice to him. He represents
a lot of money to this company.

172
00:11:05,998 --> 00:11:09,042
It's not Reggie Goldman
I'm worried about.

173
00:11:09,126 --> 00:11:11,670
- It's Larry Levy.
- Larry Levy?

174
00:11:12,671 --> 00:11:15,090
Larry Levy's at Fox, isn't he?

175
00:11:16,967 --> 00:11:19,177
Come on, Celia.

176
00:11:19,261 --> 00:11:22,389
There's a call for Celia
on line one.

177
00:11:22,472 --> 00:11:25,892
- Should I be looking for a job?
- Celia, are you there?

178
00:11:25,976 --> 00:11:30,314
Joel Levison's office.
Oh, Brad. Yeah.

179
00:11:30,355 --> 00:11:31,898
What?

180
00:11:31,982 --> 00:11:36,486
No, we couldn't sign Angelica Huston
for that. She's booked for two years.

181
00:11:36,570 --> 00:11:41,158
Like a ghost story,
but it's not like Ghost.

182
00:11:44,661 --> 00:11:46,830
It's a supernatural thing.

183
00:11:49,333 --> 00:11:52,044
Joel, Griffin Mill.
A friend of Jennifer's.

184
00:11:52,127 --> 00:11:55,255
No. You're Griffin Mill?
Really?

185
00:11:55,339 --> 00:11:57,257
Good to see you.
I'm a big fan of yours.

186
00:11:57,341 --> 00:12:00,010
- I have that tie.
- You do?

187
00:12:06,433 --> 00:12:08,560
Did you order for me?

188
00:12:11,021 --> 00:12:14,733
Hi. Lunching with the enemy.

189
00:12:14,816 --> 00:12:16,777
Oh, come on.

190
00:12:16,860 --> 00:12:19,988
So what's this we hear
about Larry Levy?

191
00:12:20,072 --> 00:12:23,700
Larry Levy? If he had half a brain,
he'd be dangerous.

192
00:12:25,660 --> 00:12:28,038
Aaron says he's coming
to the studio.

193
00:12:28,080 --> 00:12:32,751
Aaron says? Why would you believe
anything he says?

194
00:12:32,834 --> 00:12:35,545
He said it with authority.

195
00:12:35,629 --> 00:12:40,384
He's over there with Angelica Huston
and John Cusack.

196
00:12:40,467 --> 00:12:43,553
He's in over his head.
He's gonna drown over there.

197
00:12:44,596 --> 00:12:47,140
He's the golden boy at Fox these days.

198
00:12:47,224 --> 00:12:50,060
Did you see that thing on him
in Variety last week?

199
00:12:50,143 --> 00:12:51,686
Two pages.

200
00:12:51,770 --> 00:12:55,690
Angelica, Griffin Mill.
Good to see you. You're looking great.

201
00:12:55,774 --> 00:12:58,735
Johnny, Griffin Mill.
A big fan of yours.

202
00:12:58,777 --> 00:13:01,863
- You gonna be in Telluride this year?
- Probably in Park City.

203
00:13:01,947 --> 00:13:04,116
Great. We'll see you there.

204
00:13:05,784 --> 00:13:11,206
- What's happening with Glass Box?
- Let's not talk about Hollywood.

205
00:13:11,289 --> 00:13:13,834
We're educated people.

206
00:13:18,964 --> 00:13:21,091
I'll call you later.

207
00:13:53,456 --> 00:13:55,917
- Talk to somebody about this.
- What?

208
00:13:56,001 --> 00:13:58,795
- You've gotten 5 postcards in 2 weeks.
- Seven, actually.

209
00:13:58,879 --> 00:14:01,464
Why don't you talk to Studio Security?

210
00:14:01,548 --> 00:14:03,675
I should call Walter Stuckel
and say what?

211
00:14:03,758 --> 00:14:08,471
'Someone's sending me poison letters
and I would like for you to make me...

212
00:14:08,513 --> 00:14:12,142
the object of more ridicule now that
things are really shaky for me here.(

213
00:14:12,225 --> 00:14:13,685
I don't think so.

214
00:14:13,727 --> 00:14:15,770
I think they're coming from a writer.

215
00:14:15,854 --> 00:14:17,814
- Which one?
- Take your pick.

216
00:14:20,358 --> 00:14:22,694
- Is there anything else?
- Yes, your attorney phoned.

217
00:14:22,777 --> 00:14:25,614
He wants you to attend a party
at his house tonight.

218
00:14:25,697 --> 00:14:28,658
- Tell him I'm at a screening.
- Not that attorney. It's Dick Mellen.

219
00:14:28,700 --> 00:14:30,160
What time?

220
00:14:30,201 --> 00:14:33,204
Cocktails at 7:30, dinner at 8:00.
Bring a date.

221
00:14:33,246 --> 00:14:35,498
And Bonnie Sherow is here to see you.

222
00:14:35,582 --> 00:14:38,543
Send her in.
Oh, here she is.

223
00:14:38,585 --> 00:14:41,671
Can we go to the Springs this weekend?

224
00:14:41,755 --> 00:14:46,343
I want to have a massage,
a long soak in a hot tub...

225
00:14:46,384 --> 00:14:49,638
and have Margaritas administered
intravenously.

226
00:14:49,721 --> 00:14:51,931
I have a party at Dick Mellen's.
You want to come?

227
00:14:52,015 --> 00:14:54,559
God, movie stars and power players.

228
00:14:54,643 --> 00:14:57,562
- And Vodka.
- Sure.

229
