Yes. I was there once on
a location scout with Steven Spielberg.

469
00:32:37,620 --> 00:32:40,039
I lived there for a year.

470
00:32:40,123 --> 00:32:42,292
Student year abroad.

471
00:32:42,333 --> 00:32:45,169
I wish I'd done that.

472
00:32:45,253 --> 00:32:48,590
I think about it a lot.
I'll never forget it.

473
00:32:48,673 --> 00:32:51,175
You should write about it.

474
00:32:51,259 --> 00:32:53,803
I did.
Don't you remember?

475
00:32:55,013 --> 00:32:56,472
What?

476
00:32:58,766 --> 00:33:03,896
My idea about the American student
who goes to Japan.

477
00:33:03,980 --> 00:33:07,150
That was my pitch, the one you were
supposed to get back to me on.

478
00:33:07,191 --> 00:33:10,069
- You don't remember, do you?
- Of course I remember.

479
00:33:12,530 --> 00:33:15,158
You never got back to me.

480
00:33:15,199 --> 00:33:17,285
Listen.

481
00:33:17,368 --> 00:33:22,498
I was an asshole, all right?
It comes with the job.

482
00:33:22,540 --> 00:33:24,667
I'm really sorry.

483
00:33:26,961 --> 00:33:30,173
I know how angry you must've been.
I'll make it up to you.

484
00:33:30,214 --> 00:33:31,841
That's why I'm here.

485
00:33:31,883 --> 00:33:35,428
I'm gonna give you a deal, David.

486
00:33:35,511 --> 00:33:39,223
I won't guarantee you I'll make
the movie, but I will give you a shot.

487
00:33:43,061 --> 00:33:47,899
Let's just stop all the postcard shit,
all right?

488
00:33:47,982 --> 00:33:50,777
I'm here to say
that I would like...

489
00:33:50,860 --> 00:33:52,779
to start over.

490
00:33:54,405 --> 00:33:55,865
Friends.

491
00:33:57,617 --> 00:34:00,370
Fuck you, man.
You're a liar.

492
00:34:00,411 --> 00:34:02,413
You're stepping over the line.

493
00:34:02,497 --> 00:34:04,749
You didn't come here
to see The Bicycle Thief.

494
00:34:04,791 --> 00:34:07,919
You came in five minutes
before the picture ended.

495
00:34:08,002 --> 00:34:10,421
Nearly tripped over my feet.

496
00:34:11,798 --> 00:34:13,758
Did you call my house?

497
00:34:15,718 --> 00:34:17,595
Speak to the Ice Queen?

498
00:34:19,305 --> 00:34:22,600
You'd like her.
She's a lot like you.

499
00:34:22,642 --> 00:34:24,102
All heart.

500
00:34:30,233 --> 00:34:34,445
You're on my list, pal.
Nothing's gonna change that.

501
00:34:38,282 --> 00:34:41,911
See you in the next reel, asshole.

502
00:35:29,792 --> 00:35:33,713
It's a nice boat you got there,
movie exec.

503
00:35:33,796 --> 00:35:37,091
It's me, the writer.
Still want to buy my story?

504
00:35:37,175 --> 00:35:40,678
I told you I'd deal. Stop by the studio.
We'll work something out.

505
00:35:40,761 --> 00:35:43,681
And who will I ask for?

506
00:35:43,723 --> 00:35:45,182
Larry Levy?

507
00:35:47,184 --> 00:35:49,145
What's Larry Levy got to do with this?

508
00:35:50,229 --> 00:35:52,523
- How do you know about Larry Levy?
- Don't you read the trades?

509
00:35:52,607 --> 00:35:55,818
New York Times business section?
He's movin' in, you're movin' out.

510
00:35:55,902 --> 00:35:58,613
You can't make a deal, they say.
Yesterday's news.

511
00:35:58,696 --> 00:36:00,615
Wait a minute.

512
00:36:02,074 --> 00:36:04,535
Can I borrow your mobile phone?

513
00:36:04,619 --> 00:36:08,205
Larry Levy.
Larry, David Kahane here.

514
00:36:08,247 --> 00:36:12,209
Guess who's making promises
about getting pictures made...

515
00:36:12,251 --> 00:36:14,879
to writers in parking lots?

516
00:36:14,921 --> 00:36:17,965
Guess what dumb
son of a bitch executive...

517
00:36:18,049 --> 00:36:22,136
is trying to take advantage of me?

518
00:36:22,219 --> 00:36:25,973
Do you realize how unstoppable
this guy is?

519
00:36:26,057 --> 00:36:28,392
You know,
I cannot wait...

520
00:36:28,434 --> 00:36:33,481
to tell the world that when Griffin Mill
can't cut the pressure at work...

521
00:36:33,564 --> 00:36:36,567
he drives out to Pasadena...

522
00:36:36,651 --> 00:36:39,570
to pick fights with writers.

523
00:36:40,905 --> 00:36:42,907
Tell Larry Levy to call me.

524
00:36:42,990 --> 00:36:48,454
The word is out that he's going to start
making meaningful pictures for a change.

525
00:36:48,496 --> 00:36:51,666
Let's forget this.
Just stop all the postcard shit!

526
00:36:51,749 --> 00:36:53,959
I don't write postcards!
I write scripts!

527
00:36:54,043 --> 00:36:57,254
- We're both wrong.
- No, you're wrong, buddy!

528
00:36:57,338 --> 00:37:00,007
You're in over your head.
That's why you're losing your job.

529
00:37:00,091 --> 00:37:02,218
Then what are you gonna do?

530
00:37:03,344 --> 00:37:05,721
I can write.
What can you do?

531
00:37:10,476 --> 00:37:12,728
I said, let's forget this.

532
00:37:17,483 --> 00:37:19,443
Ah, shit.

533
00:37:21,570 --> 00:37:23,781
Mill, you okay?

534
00:37:32,206 --> 00:37:34,942
Keep it to yourself!

535
00:37:35,126 --> 00:37:37,711
Keep it to yourself!

536
00:38:03,362 --> 00:38:04,822
Kahane?

537
00:39:25,945 --> 00:39:29,740
That's interesting.
Who's writing this movie?

538
00:39:29,782 --> 00:39:33,327
Who wrote the new ending
to Fatal Attraction? The audience.

539
00:39:33,410 --> 00:39:36,372
A million screenwriters
from the audience wrote that.

540
00:39:36,455 --> 00:39:40,292
Who's to say what it would have done
if you had left the original ending?

541
00:39:40,376 --> 00:39:44,296
You're right, but you can say that it's
done almost 300 million worldwide...

542
00:39:44,338 --> 00:39:46,674
with the new ending.

543
00:39:46,799 --> 00:39:50,427
Larry Levy, I don't believe you've met
my assistant, Whitney Gersh.

544
00:39:50,511 --> 00:39:53,097
- No, I haven't.
- It's a pleasure to meet you.

545
00:39:55,265 --> 00:39:57,935
How's your picture?
It just tested last week.

546
00:39:57,977 --> 00:40:01,605
It's doing well.
It was our first test.

547
00:40:01,689 --> 00:40:03,607
Excuse me, Walter.

548
00:40:03,649 --> 00:40:08,070
Joel, Griffin isn't in, but I think
we really have to start this meeting.

549
00:40:08,153 --> 00:40:10,406
Okay, Celia. Thank you.

550
00:40:13,117 --> 00:40:15,327
Remember a movie called D.O.A.?

551
00:40:15,411 --> 00:40:17,621
Sure I do.
Eddie O'Brien and Pam Britton.

552
00:40:17,663 --> 00:40:21,166
Disney did a remake in '87 or '88.

553
00:40:21,250 --> 00:40:24,086
I think we've got
pretty much the same situation here.

554
00:40:24,169 --> 00:40:26,630
Keep our noses clean, Walter.

555
00:40:30,092 --> 00:40:32,594
It's a shame to waste a picture.

556
00:40:32,678 --> 00:40:36,890
Who said we're wasting the picture?
Where did that come from?

557
00:40:36,974 --> 00:40:39,768
You know what's interesting?
We're all too busy-

558
00:40:39,852 --> 00:40:44,690
Griffin, you're really late.
They're waiting inside.

559
00:40:44,773 --> 00:40:48,193
To actually rub shoulders
with the great unwashed?

560
00:40:48,277 --> 00:40:51,530
We need to give them
the kind of pictures they want...

561
00:40:51,613 --> 00:40:53,740
not the kind
writers want to give them.

562
00:41:01,081 --> 00:41:04,084
- Hello. Sorry I'm late.
- You certainly are.

563
00:41:08,088 --> 00:41:10,340
A few minutes in the office
would be fine.

564
00:41:11,216 --> 00:41:13,635
Griffin, you missed
the formal welcoming ceremony.

565
00:41:13,719 --> 00:41:16,680
You know Larry Levy.

566
00:41:16,763 --> 00:41:18,807
Of course. Hi, Larry.

567
00:41:20,225 --> 00:41:21,643
Hi, Griffin.

568
00:41:21,727 --> 00:41:23,645
Larry was able to leave Fox
a week earlier than he thought...

569
00:41:23,729 --> 00:41:25,856
and has come aboard
as of this morning.

570
00:41:25,898 --> 00:41:30,986
- Great. Let's start.
- Larry was in the middle of something.

571
00:41:31,069 --> 00:41:34,656
No, I wasn't. I was just killing time
waiting for Griffin.

572
00:41:34,740 --> 00:41:37,743
No, finish.
What were you saying?

573
00:41:37,826 --> 00:41:42,247
I was saying I've yet to meet a writer
who could change water into wine...

574
00:41:42,331 --> 00:41:44,833
and we have a tendency
to treat them like that.

575
00:41:45,918 --> 00:41:48,170
Not at this studio.

576
00:41:48,253 --> 00:41:52,174
A million and a half of these scripts.
It's nuts.

577
00:41:52,257 --> 00:41:54,551
And I think avoidable.

578
00:41:54,635 --> 00:41:58,639
Let me ask you. When was the last time
you bought a ticket to see a movie?

579
00:41:58,722 --> 00:42:02,643
- You actually paid your own money?
- Last night.

580
00:42:02,726 --> 00:42:04,895
Pasadena. The Bicycle Thief.

581
00:42:04,978 --> 00:42:08,190
- You saw The Bicycle Thief?
- I love that. It's a great film.

582
00:42:08,273 --> 00:42:11,068
It's an art movie. It doesn't count.
We're talking about movie movies.

583
00:42:11,109 --> 00:42:13,070
Jesus, people.

584
00:42:13,111 --> 00:42:16,031
I'm just saying there's time
and money to be saved...

585
00:42:16,114 --> 00:42:18,825
if we came up with these stories
on our own.

586
00:42:18,909 --> 00:42:21,912
- Where are these stories coming from?
- Anywhere. It doesn't matter.

587
00:42:23,497 --> 00:42:26,375
The newspaper.
Pick any story.

588
00:42:29,628 --> 00:42:32,673
'Immigrants protest budget cuts
in literacy program.'

589
00:42:32,756 --> 00:42:36,218
Human spirit overcoming human adversity.
Sounds like Horatio Alger in the barrio.

590
00:42:36,301 --> 00:42:39,262
Put Jimmy Smits in it and you've got
a sexy Stand and Deliver.

591
00:42:39,346 --> 00:42:42,724
- Next. Come on.
- This isn't my field.

592
00:42:42,808 --> 00:42:45,519
It doesn't matter. Give it a shot.
You can't lose here.

593
00:42:48,522 --> 00:42:52,818
How about 'Mud slide kills 60
in slums of Chili'?

594
00:42:52,901 --> 00:42:56,279
That's good. Triumph over tragedy.
Sounds like a John Boorman picture.

595
00:42:56,363 --> 00:42:59,616
Slap a happy ending on it,
the script will write itself.

596
00:42:59,658 --> 00:43:03,286
- Bonnie. Give me the paper.
- I don't know, Larry.

597
00:43:03,328 --> 00:43:05,288
Give it a shot.

598
00:43:06,999 --> 00:43:10,377
'Further bond losses
push Dow down 7.15.'

599
00:43:11,294 --> 00:43:14,047
- I see Connery as Bond.
- That's funny.

600
00:43:14,131 --> 00:43:17,801
It's a good thing Oliver Stone wasn't
listening to you. Where would we be?

601
00:43:17,843 --> 00:43:22,139
We would have been spared
sitting through Wall Street.

602
00:43:22,180 --> 00:43:25,851
- What did Wall Street do worldwide?
- 70, 75, maybe 80.

603
00:43:25,934 --> 00:43:29,146
$80 million,
a couple Oscars.

604
00:43:29,229 --> 00:43:33,275
I think Larry's point is well taken.
Let's move on.

605
00:43:33,358 --> 00:43:36,820
Can you give us an update
on the Taylor-Hackford project?

606
00:43:36,903 --> 00:43:38,905
Griffin?

607
00:43:38,989 --> 00:43:40,407
Yeah.

608
00:43:41,700 --> 00:43:44,244
I was thinking what
an interesting concept it is...

609
00:43:44,327 --> 00:43:48,623
to eliminate the writer
from the artistic process.

610
00:43:49,541 --> 00:43:54,463
If we can get rid of the actors and
directors, maybe we've got something.

611
00:43:59,885 --> 00:44:01,303
Hello, Walter.

612
00:44:01,386 --> 00:44:03,680
Make yourself at home.

613
00:44:03,764 --> 00:44:07,476
Mr. Mill, I understand you were late
coming in this morning.

614
00:44:07,559 --> 00:44:09,811
You all right?

615
00:44:09,853 --> 00:44:11,480
I'm fine.

616
00:44:11,563 --> 00:44:13,690
I appreciate your concern.

617
00:44:15,108 --> 00:44:17,486
What can I do for you?

618
00:44:17,569 --> 00:44:21,281
Don't tell me you came here
to pitch me a story?

619
00:44:21,323 --> 00:44:23,742
That's exactly what I've come to do.

620
00:44:23,825 --> 00:44:26,870
It's a good one, too.
It's about a writer, sort of.

621
00:44:26,953 --> 00:44:28,371
David Kahane.

622
00:44:31,249 --> 00:44:33,668
Who's David Kahane?

623
00:44:33,710 --> 00:44:37,297
- You met him.
- I meet a lot of writers.

624
00:44:37,380 --> 00:44:42,969
But this writer was murdered last night
in back of the Rialto Theater.

625
00:44:43,011 --> 00:44:44,513
Murdered?

626
00:44:44,596 --> 00:44:48,642
Come to think of it, Pasadena's
as good a place to die as any.

627
00:44:50,018 --> 00:44:51,978
What's the story?

628
00:44:52,020 --> 00:44:56,107
In 25 words or less?
Okay.

629
00:44:56,191 --> 00:44:59,027
Movie exec calls writer.
Girlfriend says he's at the movies.

630
00:44:59,069 --> 00:45:02,405
Exec goes to movies, meets writer,
drinks with writer.

631
00:45:02,489 --> 00:45:06,034
Writer gets conked and dies
in 4 inches of dirty water.

632
00:45:06,117 --> 00:45:08,411
Movie exec is in deep shit.

633
00:45:09,538 --> 00:45:11,539
What do you think?

634
00:45:11,581 --> 00:45:15,085
That's more than 25 words.
And it's bullshit.

635
00:45:15,168 --> 00:45:19,047
Pasadena homicide doesn't think so.
They've got a complete report.

636
00:45:20,090 --> 00:45:24,386
You met Kahane at the Rialto,
got drunk with him. He left before you.

637
00:45:24,427 --> 00:45:27,722
That's the last time anyone
saw him alive, except you, maybe.

638
00:45:28,932 --> 00:45:31,768
Why are you denying this?

639
00:45:31,851 --> 00:45:35,230
Well, what do the police think?

640
00:45:35,313 --> 00:45:38,066
They think it's a botched robbery.

641
00:45:39,901 --> 00:45:44,864
The window of his car was busted.
He surprised someone taking the radio.

642
00:45:44,948 --> 00:45:47,242
There was a fight, he was killed.

643
00:45:47,284 --> 00:45:50,245
I didn't kill him, Walter.

644
00:45:50,328 --> 00:45:54,874
But I went to see him.
I know I said I didn't, but I did.

645
00:45:54,958 --> 00:45:57,043
Why'd you lie to me?

646
00:45:58,920 --> 00:46:01,256
Now's not a very good time for me.

647
00:46:01,339 --> 00:46:04,884
Haven't you heard the rumors?
I'm on my way out.

648
00:46:04,926 --> 00:46:07,429
Just what I need,
a little more controversy.

649
00:46:07,512 --> 00:46:09,431
It's not a good time.

650
00:46:10,849 --> 00:46:13,143
Look.

651
00:46:13,226 --> 00:46:16,813
I'm in charge of studio security
in every definition of the word.

652
00:46:16,896 --> 00:46:22,444
Which means it is my job to take care
of a studio executive should he be...

653
00:46:22,527 --> 00:46:25,780
under suspicion of murder
at a time when profits are down...

654
00:46:25,864 --> 00:46:28,283
and the company is vulnerable
for a takeover.

655
00:46:28,324 --> 00:46:31,494
It is my job to keep this
very, very quiet!

656
00:46:32,912 --> 00:46:34,998
Do you want to help?

657
00:46:35,081 --> 00:46:37,959
- Of course.
- Then stop lying.

658
00:46:38,001 --> 00:46:40,587
- How many times did you meet with him?
- Once.

659
00:46:41,796 --> 00:46:44,340
- Not counting last night.
- Not counting last night.

660
00:46:44,424 --> 00:46:46,676
Why'd you go all the way to Pasadena
to meet him?

661
00:46:46,760 --> 00:46:49,679
He had an idea I was interested in.
I wanted to talk to him right away.

662
00:46:49,763 --> 00:46:54,559
Was his girlfriend a friend, too?
Think fast.

663
00:46:54,642 --> 00:46:57,270
Jesus Christ, Walter.
What is this?

664
00:46:57,312 --> 00:47:00,482
The third degree. Wait until the police
start asking questions.

665
00:47:00,565 --> 00:47:04,027
I'll go to the police now.
You come with me.

666
00:47:04,110 --> 00:47:06,446
You're acting like someone
who's guilty.

667
00:47:06,488 --> 00:47:08,490
You're not guilty, are you?

668
00:47:08,531 --> 00:47:10,784
I'm not a murderer.

669
00:47:28,009 --> 00:47:30,011
Bad news?

670
00:47:30,094 --> 00:47:31,513
What?

671
00:47:31,596 --> 00:47:34,516
The fax.
Is it bad news?

672
00:47:36,976 --> 00:47:38,561
Business as usual.

673
00:47:40,230 --> 00:47:44,025
The Hollywood system
did not murder David Kahane.

674
00:47:44,067 --> 00:47:47,237
Not the $98 million movie,
not the $12 million actor.

675
00:47:47,320 --> 00:47:52,951
Not even the million dollar deal
that David Kahane never landed.

676
00:47:53,034 --> 00:47:56,120
The most that we can pin on Hollywood...

677
00:47:56,204 --> 00:47:59,666
is assault with intent to kill.

678
00:47:59,707 --> 00:48:04,546
Because society is responsible
for this particular murder.

679
00:48:04,587 --> 00:48:06,714
It is to society we must look...

680
00:48:06,798 --> 00:48:10,552
if we are to have justice
for that crime.

681
00:48:10,593 --> 00:48:13,346
Because someone in the night...

682
00:48:13,388 --> 00:48:15,598
killed David Kahane.

683
00:48:15,682 --> 00:48:18,101
And that person
will have to bear the guilt.

684
00:48:19,644 --> 00:48:22,063
And if David were here now...

685
00:48:22,105 --> 00:48:24,649
I know in my heart
that he would say...

686
00:48:26,067 --> 00:48:28,987
'Cut the shit, Phil.

687
00:48:29,070 --> 00:48:33,032
What did you learn from this?
Did you learn anything from this?(

688
00:48:33,074 --> 00:48:36,202
And I'd say, 'Yeah, David,
I've learned a lot.

689
00:48:36,244 --> 00:48:39,205
We here will take it from here.

690
00:48:39,247 --> 00:48:43,584
And the next time we sell a script
for a million dollars...

691
00:48:43,626 --> 00:48:46,963
and nail some shit-bag producer
to the wall, we'll say...

692
00:48:47,046 --> 00:48:49,507
That's another one for David Kahane.(

693
00:48:53,136 --> 00:48:57,015
David was working on something the day
he died. I'd like to share it with you.

694
00:48:58,391 --> 00:49:01,394
'Blackness.
A mangy dog barks.

695
00:49:01,436 --> 00:49:04,772
Garbage can lids are lifted
as derelicts in the street...

696
00:49:04,814 --> 00:49:07,275
hunt for food.

697
00:49:07,358 --> 00:49:09,777
Buzzing, as a cheap alarm clock
goes off.

698
00:49:09,861 --> 00:49:13,573
Interior. Flophouse room.
Early morning.

699
00:49:13,614 --> 00:49:16,743
A tracking shot moves
through the grimy room.

700
00:49:16,826 --> 00:49:20,413
Light streams in through holes
in yellowing window shades.

701
00:49:20,496 --> 00:49:23,166
Moths dance
in the beams of light.

702
00:49:23,249 --> 00:49:26,586
Track down along the floor.
The frayed rug.

703
00:49:26,627 --> 00:49:29,589
Stop on an old shoe.

704
00:49:29,630 --> 00:49:31,341
It's empty.

705
00:49:35,595 --> 00:49:37,680
That's as far as he got.

706
00:49:39,057 --> 00:49:41,517
That's the last thing he wrote.

707
00:49:42,393 --> 00:49:44,604
So long, Dave.

708
00:49:44,645 --> 00:49:46,856
Fade out.

709
00:49:46,939 --> 00:49:48,357
Thank you.

710
00:50:04,665 --> 00:50:07,168
Who are you?
You're not a writer.

711
00:50:08,920 --> 00:50:11,255
No, I'm Griffin Mill.

712
00:50:11,339 --> 00:50:13,257
We spoke the night David-

713
00:50:13,341 --> 00:50:16,177
Blue sea, white sea.
Yes.

714
00:50:16,219 --> 00:50:18,513
- It turned out you were right.
- What?

715
00:50:18,596 --> 00:50:21,015
It was a red sea.

716
00:50:21,099 --> 00:50:22,850
Oh, yeah.

717
00:50:25,311 --> 00:50:28,481
You're the only person I know here.

718
00:50:28,523 --> 00:50:31,400
I'm really sorry about David.

719
00:50:31,484 --> 00:50:34,570
He was a talent.

720
00:50:35,738 --> 00:50:37,949
You really think so?

721
00:50:38,032 --> 00:50:41,285
I always suspected he was...

722
00:50:41,369 --> 00:50:43,996
uniquely untalented.

723
00:50:45,540 --> 00:50:48,709
It's nice of you to say that. It was
nice of you to come. You didn't have to.

724
00:50:48,793 --> 00:50:50,211
I did.

725
00:50:50,294 --> 00:50:54,841
You know, I was probably the last person
to see him alive.

726
00:50:54,882 --> 00:50:57,218
The police told me.

727
00:50:57,260 --> 00:50:59,387
Not quite the last, surely.

728
00:51:02,557 --> 00:51:05,768
I'm sure this is a terrible time
for you.

729
00:51:05,852 --> 00:51:08,187
Is there anything you need?

730
00:51:08,229 --> 00:51:12,942
No, really.
I don't feel bad.

731
00:51:13,025 --> 00:51:15,903
It's like when my parents died.

732
00:51:15,945 --> 00:51:19,490
I didn't feel anything at all.
They were just gone.

733
00:51:21,200 --> 00:51:24,412
I'm sure it hasn't sunk in yet.

734
00:51:24,495 --> 00:51:26,247
That was years ago.

735
00:51:26,289 --> 00:51:29,083
No, I meant David.

736
00:51:29,125 --> 00:51:31,002
Oh, God.

737
00:51:31,085 --> 00:51:34,088
These people.
I don't like it here.

738
00:51:34,171 --> 00:51:37,758
They're all expecting me
to grieve and mourn.

739
00:51:37,842 --> 00:51:40,136
I can't talk to them.

740
00:51:41,887 --> 00:51:47,018
David's gone and
I'm somewhere else already.

741
00:51:47,101 --> 00:51:49,937
- Will you take me home?
- What?

742
00:51:49,979 --> 00:51:52,732
Will you take me home?

743
00:51:52,773 --> 00:51:55,568
Sure. I'm right here.

744
00:52:32,563 --> 00:52:35,191
These are very interesting.
I like them.

745
00:52:35,274 --> 00:52:38,903
- Would you like a drink?
- No, thanks.

746
00:52:38,986 --> 00:52:42,907
Where do you show?
What gallery? Who's your dealer?

747
00:52:42,990 --> 00:52:45,409
I don't have a dealer.

748
00:52:45,493 --> 00:52:48,454
I couldn't sell these.
They're never finished. Biccy?

749
00:52:50,039 --> 00:52:53,000
No, thanks.
They're never finished?

750
00:52:53,084 --> 00:52:57,546
No, they're just what I do
for myself.

751
00:52:57,588 --> 00:53:00,132
What I feel.

752
00:53:00,216 --> 00:53:02,885
You ask lots of questions, Mr. Mill.

753
00:53:02,968 --> 00:53:06,722
Just like the police.
That's all they did, ask questions.

754
00:53:08,432 --> 00:53:10,351
They asked me a lot about you.

755
00:53:10,434 --> 00:53:12,144
Did they?

756
00:53:12,228 --> 00:53:14,146
How long we'd known each other.

757
00:53:14,230 --> 00:53:16,232
If you'd ever been
to the house before.

758
00:53:16,315 --> 00:53:21,153
- They have to ask those questions.
- I don't see why.

759
00:53:21,237 --> 00:53:23,489
Because that's what police do.

760
00:53:24,532 --> 00:53:27,701
- Can I ask you a question?
- Sure.

761
00:53:27,785 --> 00:53:30,538
Why was it so important
to see David that night?

762
00:53:30,621 --> 00:53:32,706
What was so urgent?

763
00:53:34,375 --> 00:53:37,253
He pitched me a story
a few months ago.

764
00:53:37,336 --> 00:53:39,630
- The Japan story?
- Yes, the Japan story.

765
00:53:39,713 --> 00:53:43,259
I liked it but it needed work,
especially the ending.

766
00:53:43,342 --> 00:53:46,137
I was sitting in my office...

767
00:53:46,220 --> 00:53:49,181
and it suddenly occurred to me
how to make the ending work.

768
00:53:49,265 --> 00:53:51,392
So what was it?

769
00:53:51,475 --> 00:53:52,893
What?

770
00:53:52,977 --> 00:53:55,938
Your idea for the ending.

771
00:53:56,021 --> 00:53:58,023
Up.

772
00:53:58,107 --> 00:54:00,276
Up? What does that mean?

773
00:54:00,359 --> 00:54:03,112
As opposed to down. Moods.

774
00:54:03,195 --> 00:54:06,365
You know, happy as opposed to sad.
Hopeful as opposed to depressing.

775
00:54:06,448 --> 00:54:10,119
- What did you think of his ending?
- I never read it.

776
00:54:12,037 --> 00:54:14,665
- You never read it?
- Nope.

777
00:54:14,748 --> 00:54:17,167
I don't like reading.

778
00:54:17,251 --> 00:54:22,423
- Do you like books?
- I like words and letters.

779
00:54:22,506 --> 00:54:24,758
But I'm not crazy
about complete sentences.

780
00:54:26,510 --> 00:54:29,013
What did he think?

781
00:54:29,096 --> 00:54:32,850
He walked out on me.
I don't think David liked me.

782
00:54:32,933 --> 00:54:36,854
I think he just didn't like
happy endings.

783
00:54:40,608 --> 00:54:42,776
Put your face here.

784
00:54:44,320 --> 00:54:45,738
Great.

785
00:54:47,906 --> 00:54:50,492
What are you doing?
You aren't going to paint me, are you?

786
00:54:50,576 --> 00:54:53,829
I might put you
in one of my paintings.

787
00:54:53,871 --> 00:54:57,541
There's one I want to do
of an Icelandic hero.

788
00:54:57,625 --> 00:55:00,628
He's a thief
and he's made of fire.

789
00:55:00,711 --> 00:55:03,255
- You might not like that.
- Why not?

790
00:55:03,339 --> 00:55:06,050
Because you're in the movies...

791
00:55:06,133 --> 00:55:10,054
and in movies you can't have thieves
as heroes, can you?

792
00:55:10,137 --> 00:55:13,724
I don't know about that. We have a long
tradition of gangsters in movies.

793
00:55:13,807 --> 00:55:17,519
Yes, but they always have to suffer
for their crimes, don't they?

794
00:55:19,104 --> 00:55:21,273
We should pay for our crimes,
shouldn't we?

795
00:55:21,357 --> 00:55:25,694
I think knowing you've committed a crime
is suffering enough.

796
00:55:25,736 --> 00:55:27,738
If you don't suffer...

797
00:55:27,821 --> 00:55:31,533
maybe it wasn't a crime after all.

798
00:55:31,575 --> 00:55:34,119
Anyway, what difference does it make?

799
00:55:34,203 --> 00:55:37,456
It has nothing to do
with how things really are.

800
00:55:41,794 --> 00:55:44,463
Do you really believe that?

801
00:55:44,546 --> 00:55:47,925
I don't know what I believe, Mr. Mill.

802
00:55:48,008 --> 00:55:50,803
It's just what I feel.

803
00:55:52,471 --> 00:55:56,266
You know what you are,
June whatever-your-name-is?

804
00:55:56,350 --> 00:55:58,018
A pragmatic anarchist.

805
00:55:59,478 --> 00:56:01,438
Is that what I am?

806
00:56:01,480 --> 00:56:03,607
I never was sure.

807
00:56:08,112 --> 00:56:10,531
Can I just pick this up?

808
00:56:11,782 --> 00:56:14,576
- Oh, it's heavy.
- Thirty-seven ounces.

809
00:56:14,618 --> 00:56:17,121
Really? Look.

810
00:56:17,162 --> 00:56:21,375
I want to thank my mother, her mother
and her father's mother who-

811
00:56:23,377 --> 00:56:24,795
Hello.

812
00:56:26,255 --> 00:56:29,758
- Meet Detective Susan Avery.
- How do you do? My partner.

813
00:56:29,842 --> 00:56:32,928
- Willa Broom.
- My pleasure. Let's go in here.

814
00:56:33,011 --> 00:56:35,848
This is the first real movie studio
Detective Avery's been to.

815
00:56:35,931 --> 00:56:38,934
- Really?
- Aside from the Universal Tour.

816
00:56:39,017 --> 00:56:41,603
I always take my family there
when they come.

817
00:56:41,687 --> 00:56:45,232
I've been there so often,
I feel like I'm ready to direct.

818
00:56:45,315 --> 00:56:49,820
You'd probably do better
than the film grads these days.

819
00:56:49,903 --> 00:56:52,573
I'm sorry I didn't call you
when I heard Kahane was dead.

820
00:56:52,656 --> 00:56:54,324
- Heard or read?
- Read.

821
00:56:54,366 --> 00:56:57,828
- Why didn't you?
- Walter asked me the same question.

822
00:56:57,911 --> 00:57:01,957
I wish I had a better answer. All
I can say is I didn't think about it.

823
00:57:04,459 --> 00:57:06,545
How did you know where
he was gonna be?

824
00:57:06,628 --> 00:57:09,965
- His wife told me-
- Girlfriend.

825
00:57:10,966 --> 00:57:12,384
Girlfriend.

826
00:57:12,467 --> 00:57:14,678
Girlfriend.
I didn't know either of them.

827
00:57:14,720 --> 00:57:17,097
I was restless,
thought I'd see the movie.

828
00:57:17,181 --> 00:57:20,559
If he was there, I'd talk to him
about a job I thought he was good for.

829
00:57:20,642 --> 00:57:22,811
You got to the theater,
saw him and?

830
00:57:22,853 --> 00:57:25,522
We had a drink at a Japanese place.

831
00:57:25,606 --> 00:57:29,484
It was a wild, incredible scene.
It was like Tokyo.

832
00:57:29,568 --> 00:57:32,404
He left before you.
Why didn't you leave together?

833
00:57:32,487 --> 00:57:35,115
It was an incredible scene.
I was having a great time.

834
00:57:35,198 --> 00:57:37,034
Why didn't you stay longer?

835
00:57:37,117 --> 00:57:41,330
People stopped singing. Then it was just
a bar and I don't drink.

836
00:57:41,413 --> 00:57:44,333
- You drank with him.
- When in Rome-

837
00:57:44,416 --> 00:57:48,378
Did you know him socially?
Been to his house?

838
00:57:48,462 --> 00:57:50,505
Know anything about him personally?

839
00:57:52,424 --> 00:57:55,344
We'll let you get back to work now.

840
00:57:57,888 --> 00:57:59,890
What's bothering you?

841
00:57:59,973 --> 00:58:02,851
Well, I just have to ask.

842
00:58:02,893 --> 00:58:06,730
Did you see him in the parking lot
after you left?

843
00:58:06,813 --> 00:58:10,400
No, I parked on the street.
I drive a Range Rover...

844
00:58:10,484 --> 00:58:12,903
so I feel safer
when it's visible.

845
00:58:12,986 --> 00:58:15,614
Who's gonna smash a window
if it's on the street?

846
00:58:15,697 --> 00:58:19,159
If you had a shitty car,
you would've parked in the parking lot?

847
00:58:19,242 --> 00:58:22,120
If I had a shitty car,
I might be a dead man.

848
00:58:22,204 --> 00:58:25,582
Somehow I think you're too lucky
for that.

849
00:58:25,624 --> 00:58:27,501
Thank you.

850
00:58:27,584 --> 00:58:30,379
Okay, 63, take three. Marker.

851
00:58:31,338 --> 00:58:33,757
Now.

852
00:58:33,840 --> 00:58:35,509
Action!

853
00:58:36,802 --> 00:58:41,098
No, goddamn it, you listen to me!
I've been around a while. I got a nose.

854
00:58:41,139 --> 00:58:44,935
This situation stinks.
It stinks of the company.

855
00:58:44,976 --> 00:58:48,814
That's right, Peterson,
the fucking CIA. Ever heard of it?

856
00:58:48,897 --> 00:58:51,191
It's the kind of operation-

857
00:58:51,274 --> 00:58:54,361
You don't understand what he's trying
to go for here.

858
00:58:54,444 --> 00:58:57,364
It's hard to listen to your argument
when you don't understand.

859
00:58:57,447 --> 00:59:01,910
- Would you shut up, please?
- Kiss my ass!

860
00:59:01,952 --> 00:59:04,287
I have to cut.
My robe cut on the drawer.

861
00:59:04,371 --> 00:59:08,708
- For Christ's sakes!
- I like this guy. He's great.

862
00:59:08,792 --> 00:59:13,672
Waters?
Can I have some Volvic, please?

863
00:59:13,755 --> 00:59:15,757
Yeah, he's great.

864
00:59:17,175 --> 00:59:20,262
I heard the police came to see you
about this dead writer.

865
00:59:20,303 --> 00:59:23,974
- Who was this guy?
- His name was David Kahane.

866
00:59:24,057 --> 00:59:27,102
I never heard of him.
We ever hire him for anything?

867
00:59:27,144 --> 00:59:30,147
I was thinking about it.

868
00:59:30,188 --> 00:59:33,984
He pitched me a story.
I went there to talk to him about it.

869
00:59:34,085 --> 00:59:39,614
Jesus. Poor bastard. Just when his ship
comes in, some bastard blasts him-

870
00:59:39,698 --> 00:59:42,325
I don't want to criticize you...

871
00:59:42,367 --> 00:59:45,412
but I'm supposed to be talking
on the phone.

872
00:59:45,495 --> 00:59:47,330
Are the cops still bothering you?

873
00:59:47,414 --> 00:59:51,918
- No. No, I don't think so.
- Let Stuckel handle it.

874
00:59:52,002 --> 00:59:56,131
We'll give them passes to a screening.
They can sit behind Michelle Pfeiffer.

875
00:59:56,173 --> 00:59:58,383
They'll leave you alone.

876
00:59:59,676 --> 01:00:03,305
A guy named Joe Gillis called.

877
01:00:03,346 --> 01:00:08,018
He wants you to meet him at the
St. James Club at 10:00 on the patio.

878
01:00:08,101 --> 01:00:12,105
- Never heard of him.
- He said you'd know him.

879
01:00:12,189 --> 01:00:14,149
Anybody know who Joe Gillis is?

880
01:00:14,232 --> 01:00:16,943
He's a character William Holden played
in Sunset Boulevard.

881
01:00:17,027 --> 01:00:21,281
- The writer killed by a movie star.
- Gloria Swanson.

882
01:00:25,744 --> 01:00:29,497
Oh, that guy. Last week he said
he was Charles Foster Kane.

883
01:00:29,539 --> 01:00:32,375
A week before that
it was Rhett Butler.

884
01:00:32,417 --> 01:00:35,754
Why would they think I would kill
my own sister's husband?

885
01:00:37,547 --> 01:00:39,716
I was in love with him.

886
01:01:20,757 --> 01:01:25,512
- Griffin? Griffin.
- Malcolm McDowell, good to see you.

887
01:01:25,595 --> 01:01:29,140
Listen. The next time
you want to badmouth me...

888
01:01:29,224 --> 01:01:31,643
have the courage
to do it to my face.

889
01:01:31,726 --> 01:01:34,187
You guys are all the same.

890
01:01:44,531 --> 01:01:46,825
- You love it there?
- I love it. It's wonderful.

891
01:01:46,908 --> 01:01:49,244
You love your career, don't you?
What is it?

892
01:01:49,327 --> 01:01:53,373
It was a complete disaster.
Look what happened in Heaven's Gate.

893
01:01:53,456 --> 01:01:54,624
We both are concerned...

894
01:01:54,708 --> 01:01:57,043
about your career.

895
01:01:57,127 --> 01:01:59,796
Where I live, I know how people
think and feel.

896
01:02:00,964 --> 01:02:05,176
Montana will end you.
It ended Cimino in Heaven's Gate.

897
01:02:05,260 --> 01:02:09,347
- Griffin Mill, hi. Andy Civella.
- Andy, how are you?

898
01:02:09,431 --> 01:02:13,101
I've got Andie MacDowell sitting over
here. You know her. She's so hot.

899
01:02:13,143 --> 01:02:15,437
- Come over and meet her.
- Still living in New York?

900
01:02:15,478 --> 01:02:18,481
I couldn't live here.
I'm allergic to happiness.

901
01:02:18,565 --> 01:02:22,485
Andie, it's good to see you again.
How are the kids?

902
01:02:22,569 --> 01:02:24,988
Great, thanks.
He's wonderful, thank you.

903
01:02:26,322 --> 01:02:28,700
You geniuses know each other.
Tom Oakley.

904
01:02:28,783 --> 01:02:31,828
- Yes, Hi, Tom.
- How are you?

905
01:02:31,911 --> 01:02:34,998
- Funny. I just saw Malcolm McDowell.
- Really?

906
01:02:35,081 --> 01:02:38,418
Roddy McDowall is related
to a cousin of my brother-in-law.

907
01:02:38,501 --> 01:02:41,171
Well, I'm not related
to either one of them.

908
01:02:51,181 --> 01:02:53,183
If I write it, I direct it.

909
01:02:53,266 --> 01:02:56,686
The last three pictures you directed
were bombs!

910
01:02:56,769 --> 01:03:00,106
Thank you for the drink.
I've got to go.

911
01:03:00,190 --> 01:03:02,150
You've got to go?

